erns of vegetation cover change in mountain regions from 2003 to 2024.(a) Spatial distribution of the percentage of vegetation cover converted from tree to grass across mountain grids. (b) Spatial distribution of the percentage of vegetation cover converted from grass to trees across mountain grids. (c) The difference between conversions from tree to grass and from grass to tree. (d) Differences in the percentage of tree-to-grass conversion between polar-facing and equatorial-facing slopes. (e) Differences in the percentage of grass-to-tree conversion between polar-facing and equatorial-facing slopes. Basemaps from Natural Earth (https://www.naturalearthdata.com/).Source data.Extended Data Fig. 6 Long-term vegetation dynamics indicated by tree coverage and LAI.(a) Spatial distribution of aspect asymmetry in Region 1 and the time series of tree coverage and LAI for these pixels on polar-facing and equatorial-facing slopes. The percentage shown in the spatial distribution map represents the proportion of selected grid cells relative to the total number of grid cells in Region 1. The selection criteria for these grid cells are detailed in Supplementary Table 4. Panels (b–d) are interpreted in the same manner as panel (a). The trendlines in (a-d) are fitted with ordinary least-squares regression. The significance of the regression slopes are evaluated using the two-sided t-test. Basemaps from Natural Earth (https://www.naturalearthdata.com/).Source data.Extended Data Fig. 7 Analysis of vegetation changes in snow-to-vegetation conversion areas.(a) Identification of snow-to-vegetation conversion areas. The percentage is the proportion of snow melting pixels to the total pixels across each mountain grid. (b) Percentage difference between polar-facing and equatorial-facing slopes in snow-to-vegetation conversion areas. (c) The category of long-term trends in aspect asymmetry in snow-to-vegetation conversion areas. (d-e) Time series of LAI for areas with more snowmelt on equ